value.value: An anatomical collection that is arranged in a line.
A region or zone on the surface of an organism that encompasses skin and any adnexa, down through muscles and bounded by underlying skeletal support structures.
The epithelial layer covering the biliary system. This includes the epithelium of the gallbladder (when present) as well as the intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts.
Any organ component layer that consists of smooth muscle tissue.
Any gaseous product of an excretory process.
Any excreted gas that is produced by the digestive tract.

definition.value: In mammals, mostly produced as a byproduct of bacterial fermentation in the gastrointestinal (GI) tract, especially the colon, and excreted through the rectum

value.value: Any portion of gas located in a part of the respiratory system.
A horizontal thickening onto which the muscles of the femur, such as the quadriceps and hamstring, attach.
Mesenchyme that is part of a developing jaw [Automatically generated definition].
An epithelium that is part of a naris [Automatically generated definition].
A vertebra that has a transverse process.
A post-anal tail that attaches outside the tail.
A transverse process that is part of a caudal vertebra.
A space or gap between the left and right central incisors, on either the upper or lower jaw.
A space or gap between the left and right central incisors on the upper jaw.
A space or gap between the left and right central incisors on the lower jaw.

Any material entity that is located in the digestive tract. This includes undigested food and liquid as well as unexcreted waste products. It also includes other entities such as ingested stones used to aid digestion. Any microbial cells or cell populations are also included.
A space or gap any two incisors. This may be a midline diastema between central incisors, or a diastema located entirely in a single jaw quadrant between lateral incisors.
Any of the sutures of the hard palate.
Anatomical surface, which is the external surface of the whole body. Examples: There is only one body surface.
The organ of hearing located on the right side of the head.
The narrowest portion of the gallbladder and distal to the cystic duct.
The organ of hearing located on the left side of the head[ncit,modified].
The parietal pleura that lines the mediastinum.
Any of several arteries that arise from the aorta and supply blood to the esophagus.
The part of the circulatory system that lies within the subcutaneous tissue layers close to the surface of the skin.
Any of the veins carrying deoxygenated blood from the subcutaneous tissue layers.
The part of the circulatory system that lies deep beneath the subcutaneous tissue layers away from the surface of the skin.
A blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood far beneath the skin usually accompanying an artery.
